{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=goon|みつ}}
{{IPAchar|/mitɨ/}} → {{IPAchar|/mitʉ/}} → {{IPAchar|/mit͡su/}}.

{{dercat|ja|txb|ine-toc-pro|ine-pro|cau-nec-pro}}
From {{der|ja|ltc|sort=みつ|-}} {{ltc-l|蜜}}. This word appears to have been nativized sooner than other [[Sino-Japanese]] vocabulary, as evidenced by the {{w|Nippo Jisho}} (1603), which transcibes this word as ''mitçu'', while similar {{m|ja|密}} is transcribed as ''mit'', preserving the coda ''-t'' from Chinese.<ref>{{R:Nippo Jisho}}</ref> Both have become ''mitsu'' in modern Japanese.

